<font color="#FF0000">THEY TRIED TO WIN</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul 29 18:49:13 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br><br>
Weren't trying to win? I beg to differ. Would you allow me to give you an example?<br><br>
We marched off LZ Stinson with a 2LT as our Commanding Officer. He was fresh out of West Point - no combat experience. You know how big our &quot;company&quot; was? Platoon size 40 to 50 men. All of our officers had been killed or wounded or had rotated, so the Battalion CO decided that it would be a good idea for Charley Company to take the field with a cherry for a Company Commander. Take a minute and think about that.<br><br>
The brass must have got a bad feeling so they sent us another officer the next day - a 2LT who became our Forward Observer. So, we had 2 officers with combined field/combat experience equal to zero. They were in charge of an infantry company in a combat zone.<br><br>
I have a picture of those two men which I took early one morning on the other side of the Tra Bong River. God was surely with us as we entered a place called the Rocket Pocket. We made no contact with the enemy.<br><br>
Lt McCullough was promoted a short while later and sent to another line company in our battalion. His fate was to receive a gunshot wound that paralyzed him. His replacement was a Captain who had an *artillery MOS*. Sorry Chet and Art, artillery ain't the same as infantry. He led us in a place called Dragon Valley. The new LT FO was walking with our 1st platoon which became 80% casualties when it hit a booby trap that consisted of 2 claymore mines. The LT received a bad head wound. I expected to see his name on The Wall. It wasn't there.<br><br>
The following day we had a listening post out a hundred meters from the main body of the company. This LISTENING POST evidentally was playing a radio! A couple of NVA came upon them and blew them away. 1 KIA and 7 wounded. All told for two days: 2KIA and 17 wounded.<br><br>
Speaking out against the Vietnam war doesn't dishonor those who fell or who were gravely wounded. I speak out because their suffering means a great deal to me, and I don't ever want to see others have to be used and abused the way we were. <br>
 <br>
I have 3 sons. Ain't no way would I allow them to be treated that way. I saw what was going on. I would protest. We have said several times in this group that we fought in different wars - even though we all served in Vietnam. I saw too much bullshit to feel any other way.<br><br>
They were trying to win the war all right. Read your history and see how many General Officers died leading their men in the US Civil War. How about the invasion of Normandy? Compare that to how many high ranking officers actually served and died in the field in Vietnam. LTC's flying around in choppers and telling us to, &quot;stay on line&quot; doesn't count.<br><br>
You can blame any you want. If the war had not been fought, millions would be alive today.<br><br>
PS to Cook,<br><br>
Not necessary for you to explain serving no more than 1 tour. 1 tour was sure as hell enough for me.
<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


